Subject: [PATCH] docs: Link to generic installation guide from contributing guide instead of duplicating info

Signed-off-by: Felicitas Pojtinger <felicitas@pojtinger.com>
---
diff --git a/docs/contributing-os.md b/docs/contributing-os.md
index 425230f69ce8ffb5700be17172f93b74e804cd52..2cb1cdb638e29bb4182cd551be750c2fc3f76c31 100644
--- a/docs/contributing-os.md
+++ b/docs/contributing-os.md
@@ -75,7 +75,7 @@ ## 3. Installing your locally built GNOME OS image to disk
 
 If you have secure boot enabled, `systemd-boot` will offer to auto-enroll the secure boot keys on the first boot.
 
-After booting, [GNOME Initial Setup](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gnome-initial-setup) will ask you to set up the system. After it has completed, the [GNOME OS proto-installer](../files/gnomeos/live/proto-installer) will automatically start and prompt you to install GNOME OS to disk, which you should do.
+After booting, you should install GNOME OS to disk by following the [install section in the installation guide](./install.md#install).
 
 ## 4. Rebuilding GNOME OS with your changes and deploying them
 
diff --git a/docs/install.md b/docs/install.md
index e3c431c344c3e2cc959ace6d61ac2c71314351c6..aa96f7538118c6ae4aefc7820b3c71b4f6c8f923 100644
--- a/docs/install.md
+++ b/docs/install.md
@@ -15,23 +15,26 @@
    > [!warning]
    > This erases all data on the USB drive.
 
-## Boot and install from USB
+## Boot from USB
 
 In order to run GNOME OS you need UEFI to be enabled, and secure boot to be disabled.
 
 1. Reboot into BIOS options and disable secure boot
 2. Boot from the USB drive
 3. Choose `GNOME OS Nightly` in the menu
-4. Go through initial setup and create a user
-5. If your destination disk contains data, erase it in GNOME Disks using `Format disk…` and selecting `No Partitioning`
+
+## Install
+
+1. Go through initial setup and create a user
+2. If your destination disk contains data, erase it in GNOME Disks using `Format disk…` and selecting `No Partitioning`
 
    > [!warning]
    > This erases all data on the disk.
 
-6. Upon logging in, a window will have proposed to install GNOME OS. Choose `Install now`
-7. Select the disk to install to, and press `Install`
-8. If the installer gives you a recovery key, your data is encrypted. Write the key down on a different device
-9. You can then continue using GNOME OS
+3. Upon logging in, a window will have proposed to install GNOME OS. Choose `Install now`
+4. Select the disk to install to, and press `Install`
+5. If the installer gives you a recovery key, your data is encrypted. Write the key down on a different device
+6. You can then continue using GNOME OS
 
 Now you should have a working GNOME OS setup on real hardware. Since GNOME OS is quite different from other Linux operating systems you should take a look at the [user guide](./using.md).
 

